<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n33172d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n33" href="#n33172d">N33 (VI.B.4)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n33all.htm#n33172d"> 172(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> maa Keru / (justifie)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The deceased whose heart or conscience had been weighed in the balance, and not found wanting, was declared to be &ldquo;<mark>ma&acirc; kheru</mark>&rdquo; &hellip;, and in papyri these words always follow the names of the persons for whom they were written. They are commonly rendered &ldquo;triumphant,&rdquo; or &ldquo;victorious,&rdquo;, &hellip;, &ldquo;juste,&rdquo; &ldquo;<mark>justifi&eacute;</mark>,&rdquo; &hellip; but their true meaning seems to be &ldquo;he whose word is right and true,&rdquo; i.e., he whose word is held to be right and true by those to whom it is addressed &hellip;. <small> E.A. Wallis Budge, <a name="BOD1" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#BOD1"><cite title="source">The Book of the Dead</cite></a>, 2nd ed. (1909) lxvf</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
